[helv 14;bd]Section III
Definition of Typesetting and Desktop Publishing
[roman 10;pl;fj]

This section introduces you to the concepts of desktop publishing and typesetting. It is intended to provide you some background on the idea behind desktop publishing and on the terminology of typesetting.


Introduction to Desktop Publishing

Anyone who has written a document, whether on a typewriter or on a computer, will remember how difficult and tedious it was to get that "special look."
   You have probably found yourself many times resizing figures at the copy center or producing another copy of the document to "see if it looks right" or perhaps wishing you had a better typewriter.
   Or maybe you didn't have the tools: "I'm out of glue ... I can't find the scissors ... I need another copy ... "

   And the list of problems can go on and on.

   Nowadays, many of these small or big "bugs" are taken care of easily with "desktop publishing" programs.

   The term "desktop publishing" refers to the ability of merging typeset text and graphics and arranging them in any way easily and quickly using a personal computer.
   Many of these  desktop publishing programs rely on the use of windows, a mouse, a toolbox, and a little of imagination.

   Most desktop publishing programs provide for multiple windows. For example, C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ has three main windows: the clipboard, the working page window, and the toolbox.

    Using the mouse is a way of writing and telling the system what to do next. For example: moving objects around the page requires the use of the mouse. The mouse pointer can change forms depending upon the application: resizing, moving, cutting.

    The toolbox is a way of giving you "an endless supply of glue" and "always having the scissors at your fingertips."
Using tools from the toolbox is just a matter of selecting them using the mouse.
     Imagination (or creation of the page) is all up to you.


