Introduction to Typesetting

The word "typesetting" refers to creating text (or an image) and then transferring it to paper. In this section we will discuss typesetting terminology only. Future sections will show you how to use typesetting control words and how to transfer this image to a printer.
  Throughout this manual  we mention various terms used in the typesetting industry. Some of these terms are given below. A glossary of terms can be found in the Appendix.

f‚o‚n‚t‚ -- The font or typeface specifies the style of the characters or what the characters look like. Examples of different Amiga font names are diamond, emerald, and sapphire.

a‚t‚t‚r‚i‚b‚u‚t‚e‚ -- This term refers to the appearance of the characters. Common  attributes are:
  italic -- slanted characters. Example: t„h„i„s„ „i„s„ „i„t„a„l„i„c„
  boldface --  darker than normal characters. Example: this is                bold
  plain  -- the normal appearance of characters.
  underlined -- a line is drawn underneath each character.
                  Example: t‚h‚i‚s‚ ‚i‚s‚ ‚u‚n‚d‚e‚r‚l‚i‚n‚e‚d‚.‚

m‚a‚r‚g‚i‚n‚ -- The space between the edge of the page and the text. There are four kinds of margins: top, bottom, left, right.

l‚e‚a‚d‚i‚n‚g‚ -- Vertical space between two lines. This distance is calculated from the baseline of one line to the baseline of the next.

s‚p‚a‚c‚i‚n‚g‚ -- Similar to leading. Distance between lines is calculated from the bottom of one line to the top of the next. Note that leading and spacing are mutually exclusive.

g‚u‚t‚t‚e‚r‚ -- Horizontal space between two columns of text. The distance between the right edge of the first block of text and the left edge of the second.

j‚u‚s‚t‚i‚f‚i‚c‚a‚t‚i‚o‚n‚ -- There are four kinds of justification:
    left -- text is placed against the left margin
    right -- text is placed against the right margin
    center -- Each line is centered between the left and right margins
    fill -- both margins are straight and spaces are stretched to fill the extra room. If spaces get stretched too far, the spaces between characters will start to stretch too (to control this spacing refer to "space stretch.")

i‚n‚d‚e‚n‚t‚a‚t‚i‚o‚n‚ -- Indentation indicates the amount of space from the left margin until the first line of a paragraph. Indentation causes text to be placed with respect to the left end of the output line. For example:
         This line is indented by five spaces.
     This line has no indentation.

m‚a‚g‚n‚i‚f‚i‚c‚a‚t‚i‚o‚n‚ -- Shrinks or enlarges characters in a block of text. C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ allows independent magnification in both the vertical and horizontal directions. This command is useful when the desired character size is not available in the current font.

s‚p‚a‚c‚e‚ ‚s‚t‚r‚e‚t‚c‚h‚ -- A "space stretch" is used in conjuction with filled justification. This command indicates the amount that spaces can be stretched before the space between characters starts to be stretched. Space stretch can be defined in any unit of measure. C‚i‚t‚y‚ ‚D‚e‚s‚k‚ defaults to a size of 12 pt (twelve points).

